  • There are 180 records in the dataset.

Multivariate analysis for numeric data¶

In [37]:
sns.pairplot(cgf_data);   # Let's study the correlation between numeric data using pairplot
The pairplot above shows a few interesting things¶

  • The histogram for education, usage, and fitness are fairly close to normal distribution, which is not unexpected.

  • The scatterplot between income and miles shows a strong correlation between income and miles - higher earners tend to walk/run more miles using the equipment.

  • There is also a strong correlation between age and income -- income increases as people get older. This is not surprising. However, we see some people whose income rises much faster than others, and then there are those whose income increases a lot slower with age. This shows up as a bifurcation in the scatterplot.
  • There is an interesting correlation between income and usage - the higher earners tend to use the equipment more often.

  • But there is a strong correlation between income and fitness - higher income people tend to be fitter.

  • There is a strong correlation between usage and miles, which makes sense. The more you use the equipment, the more miles you tend to run/walk.

  • There is a strong correlation between usage and fitness - the more you use the equipment the fitter you are likely to be.

  • There doesn't appear to be a strong correlation between education level and fitness.

  • But there is a strong correlation between education and income level - the more educated you are, the more you are likely to earn.

  • One surprising thing - there doesn't appear to be a strong correlation between age and usage, or age and fitness. This data combined with the other correlations shows that income and usage rather than age have a much stronger influence on a person's fitness.

Insights and Recommendations¶

Insights¶

The various insights have been documented alongside the analysis. They are summarized here¶
  • There are 3 products in the dataset.
  • There are 180 people in the dataset with about 100 men and 80 women in the sample.
  • The age of the people in the sample ranges from 18 to 50, so they are all adults who are not too old to use cardio equipments.
  • There is a wide range of income levels, education levels, and fitness levels within the sample population.
  • All histograms for age, income level, education level, fitness level, usage, and miles show a normal distirbution, with some of them having a skew to the right.

-

  • The products TM195 and TM498 have customers with similar demographics -- People with education level ranging from High School to college, with 25-75% lying between 14-16 years. -- Lower to middle income with median closer to 45,000 -- About average fitness conditions with median and mode at 3 -- Equally preferred by men and women.

-

  • The product TM798 has a different customer base -- People who have higher education levels with at least 14 years of education, and the 25-75% lying between 16-18 years. -- They tend to have higher income levels with median income arond 80,000. -- Customers tend to have very high fitness level with mode being level 5. -- Men prefer TM798 much more than women. The market is clearly missing out on women customers. -- It is likely that the customers of TM798 are high-earning male athletes.

-

  • For all three products, age doesn't make a difference if people's preferences.
  • For all three products, people's partnered/single status does not affect their preference.

-

Some product-independent insights from the data are

  • Using the products more often in a week increases fitness levels, for both men and women.
  • The more miles you run, the better is the fitness level.
  • Both of the above points can be utilized to market the cardio products as a means of improving fitness levels.
  • People with higher education and income levels also tend to have higher fitness levels. This can create opportunities to sell more high-end equipments.

Recommendations¶

Some recommendations to target new customers¶
  • Identify what is causing poor adoption of TM798 with women and address it. Conduct a survey to identify reasons.
  • If it is a product issue that makes it harder for women to use it, then provide feedback to the makers of TM798.
  • If it is an image problem, then design advertisement to improve adoption of the product among women.
  • Knowing that TM195 AND TM498 is more popular among lower income individuals but make up a greater volume of the sales, use promotional offers and other discounts to increase their volumes further.
  • Given the clear relationship between the use of the products and fitness levels of individuals, create advertisements extolling the health benefits of the products to drive more sales. Use data to encourage people to buy.
  • Given that customers' income levels increase with age, create targeted advertisements for people in the 40-50 year range to try to sell more products. That population will tend to have the most expendable income and will also be more conscious about health given that they are getting older.
